# Angular Structure in EM Fields — Volume I (Ch. 1–4)

## Conventions (locked)
- Time: phasor fields with **exp(-j ω t)**; ∂/∂t → -jω on phasors.
- **SI units** only.
- Read `00-NOTATION.md`, `00-FORWARD-MAP.yaml`, and `TOC/volume-I-ch01-04-FINAL.txt` before editing any section.
- Volume I: honor [HOME] / [USE SSx.y.z] / [DEFER] tags on every subsection line.
- Full series outline: `TOC/TOC-master-19chapters-ULTIMATE-V3-forward-only.txt` (official master, Ch. 1–19).
- Every `[FIG+PROB]` subsection: Problem, schematic figure with caption, all math steps, physical meaning per step.

## Forward progression (no recursion)
- Each chapter has an **inheritance section** (1.7, 2.11, 3.11, 4.11). Only these sections may list concepts deferred to later chapters.
- Elsewhere: **use** prior results via `\ref{...}` / "By Theorem ... (§x.y)" — never re-derive.
- Honor `forbidden_repeat` in `00-FORWARD-MAP.yaml` for the active chapter.

## AI drafting rules
- GCHECK cumulative policy is mandatory: new instructions refine existing governance and do not erase essential prior locks.
- Before drafting, always read/apply: `LOCK-MANIFEST.md`, `.cursor/rules/book-consistency.mdc`, `TOC/SUBSECTION-DRAFTING-CONTRACT-ULTIMATE.md`, `00-NOTATION.md`, and `00-FORWARD-MAP.yaml`.
- Draft strictly forward with line-by-line approval; do not skip subsections.
- Expand only from author bullets in `outlines/chNN/*.txt` when present.
- Do not invent references; use keys from `latex/references.bib` or mark `[CITATION NEEDED]`.
- Definitions of `Y_l^m`, `M_lm`, `N_lm`, radiation operator domain, and Maxwell equations: **once only** (see NOTATION + §3.4.1 / Ch. 1).
- Mark unverified proofs with `% PROOF: AUTHOR REVIEW`.
- Prefer `\E`, `\H`, `\Jimp` macros from `latex/macros.tex`.
- Enforce unique exposition per subsection: avoid repeated equation displays, repeated concept statements, and repeated sentence-construction templates; inherit prior content only via `\ref{...}` and targeted citation.
- Enforce unique subsection rhetoric: opening and closing paragraphs must not reuse the same framing template across subsections.
- Enforce substantial mathematical depth in every subsection: begin from accessible initial mathematical footing, then develop full derivation depth suitable for serious graduate/research readers.
- Maintain dense mathematical development after foundational setup; never trade completeness for brevity in theorem-bearing subsections.
- Place citations exactly at the claim location and prioritize original/pioneering sources plus latest validated developments.
- Keep figures minimal and schematic; include only when they materially improve equation-to-physics interpretation.
- Restrict figures to theorem-centric or concept-centric schematic diagrams with correct level labels and precise captions.
- Require explicit body-text explanation for each included figure so diagram interpretation is mathematically and physically connected to the subsection argument.
- If any theorem, equation block, or conceptual bridge needs readability support, insert a compact schematic figure in that subsection with proper caption, figure label, and direct discussion in prose.
- Disallow repeated diagrams across subsections unless a new theorem variant/regime is being established and the distinction is stated.
- Maintain chapter-wise numbering intent for equations `(chapter.index)` and references `[chapter.index]`.
- In chapter manuscript prose (`latex/ch*.tex`), avoid bullet-list exposition; define variables, figure levels, and captions inline within formal text.
- Every variable/symbol/operator in each equation must be explicitly defined at first appearance.
- Every major equation block must include both a mathematical-function explanation and a detailed physical explanation.
- Equation-explanation language must be stylistically varied across subsections; avoid repetitive explanatory sentence templates.
- Enforce chapter-wise monotone numbering for equations and references (e.g., `(1.1) -> (1.2)` and `[1.1] -> [1.2]` within a chapter).
- Use `TOC/TOC-master-19chapters-ULTIMATE-V3-forward-only.txt` as the primary 19-chapter structure.
- Use `TOC/TOC-master-19chapters-ULTIMATE-FINAL.txt` only as ownership-reference source when checking tag ancestry.
- Enforce theorem ownership from `TOC/THEOREM-HOME-MATRIX-19CH-ULTIMATE.md`: one HOME proof, all non-home chapters USE by citation only.
- Treat newly established theorem-bearing results as local `HOME` outcomes for that subsection; all later mentions must be `USE` by reference unless ownership is explicitly reassigned in governance files.
- Enforce per-subsection depth contract from `TOC/SUBSECTION-DRAFTING-CONTRACT-ULTIMATE.md`.
- Enforce citation placement and source pairing from `TOC/CITATION-CONTRACT-ULTIMATE.md`.
- Run no-recursion checks from `TOC/NO-RECURSION-AUDIT-PASS-ULTIMATE.md` before marking chapter drafts complete.
- In Volume I, every section (`X.0`, `X.1`, `X.2`, ...) must include an introductory framing paragraph before subsection flow and a summative framing paragraph after subsection flow.
- Enforce section-first drafting order in all chapters: draft section-level framing first, then subsections in sequence, then section-level summative bridge.
- Subsection-level bridge paragraphs are optional; do not force templated forward-link closings.
- Enforce approval cadence: line-by-line user approval and subsection-by-subsection progression before starting the next subsection.
- Follow `MODEL-WORKFLOW-LOCKED.md` for task-based model usage; no subsection is accepted complete without final high-rigor pass.
- Enforce locked prose style across the full book: **Version A — Classical Monograph Tone** (professional, measured, authoritative, reader-friendly scholarly flow; avoid dictation-style wording).
- Enforce continuous narrative flow in subsection prose; avoid template-fragment transitions and mechanical staging phrases.
- Enforce expanded reader-clarity narration: include foundational math and physics development from basic entry assumptions to major equations.
- Keep global expansion target at 3-5 PDF pages per subsection unless user-approved override is given.
- Include intermediate expressions, valid-domain statements, variable-range constraints, and assumption clarifications whenever they improve derivation readability.
- Increase use of conceptual schematic figures when they improve reader engagement and clarity; every figure must have label, caption, and explicit in-body interpretation.
- Disallow formulaic framing starters in final draft prose (e.g., "This subsection establishes ...", "For physical interpretation ...", "This closure has a direct ...").
- Vary sentence architecture and equation-explanation rhythm so prose remains indistinguishable from classical human-authored monograph writing.
- Apply the same anti-template requirement to section-head introductions and section-closing bridge paragraphs in every chapter.
- Ban architecture-centric prose justification in scientific narrative (no discussion of section/subsection/drafting architecture as justification).
- Ban title-head metacommentary framing (do not explain subsection titles as prose scaffolds); justify only concepts, assumptions, and equations.
- Enforce science-centric, student-comprehension-centric prose only in manuscript subsection bodies; explanatory text must contain mathematical/physical content, assumptions, validity, and measurement insight.
- Prohibit governance/process vocabulary inside manuscript explanatory paragraphs (e.g., `HOME`, `USE`, TOC/process narration, drafting-pipeline commentary).
- Enforce subsection-heading-component expansion: every technical component named in each subsection heading must be explicitly defined and explained with student-friendly clarity in expert monograph tone.
- Enforce practical depth target at approximately five PDF-equivalent pages per non-introductory subsection through genuine mathematical/physical expansion (not formatting inflation), unless the user overrides.
- Enforce citation hierarchy at point-of-claim: originator/seminal/pioneering sources first, then classical canonical monographs, then validated modern developments.
- For every law/theorem/proven concept/nontrivial reasoning sentence, place citation exactly at that sentence location; do not batch citations away from the claim.
- Always-recall lock: before and during every edit, re-apply all active governance constraints from LOCK-MANIFEST and drafting contracts.
- Prompt shortcut lock: if user sends `GCHECK <subsection-id>`, interpret it as a mandatory command to read/apply, **in order:** `LOCK-MANIFEST.md`, `TOC/GCHECK-MASTER-CUMULATIVE.md`, `.cursor/rules/book-consistency.mdc`, `TOC/SUBSECTION-DRAFTING-CONTRACT-ULTIMATE.md`, `TOC/CITATION-CONTRACT-ULTIMATE.md`, `TOC/NO-RECURSION-AUDIT-PASS-ULTIMATE.md`, `00-NOTATION.md`, and `00-FORWARD-MAP.yaml`, then draft only the requested subsection with all active locks.

## Tone
Graduate research monograph (Harrington/Collin level): precise, no survey padding, no popular OAM hype without gauge caveats from Ch. 1.
- Across all 19 chapters, maintain classical-monograph page quality comparable to Harrington, Pozar, Collin, Balanis, Jackson, and Griffiths in depth, density, sentence construction, and scholarly appearance.
- Default sentence register for chapter drafting is Version A classical monograph tone.

## Volume boundary
Do not draft Ch. 5+ content in Volume I files except brief forward pointers in §4.11.2–4.11.3.

